Idk.  It was partially because I saw some people on twitter talk about their experiences that made a couple things click.  The more I saw, the more I wondered.  So, maybe sharing a couple of my experiences can help someone.  Or maybe I'm just ranting.. either way.

I'm not really mad at anyone or blaming anyone.  I was as blind to it as everyone else.
But ADHD is always framed like a young male childs problem.  Of course no one considered it.  Of course I never thought it was anything but a me problem.

Anxiety, depression, eating disorders, substance abuse can be caused by having undiognosed ADHD and I guess I'm only just having the realization that everything I thought was it's own overwhelming and all consuming issue was really just a symptom all this time.. all these years.
15-23* same diff tho

I abused some drugs recreationally at 15-25 and I look back at the days I'd take allergy medication to get through my old job because it made it bearable and..... normal.  I remember at 15 my friend gave me ritalin and it just helped. 
Now it fucking makes sense.
@ppanda878 I took SS10 three times and no one bothered to ask why.

When you get labeled as a failure and lazy and day dreamy and careless at such a young age you carry that with you.  It's the only explanation you're given.  
I can still remember the day, in 3rd grade sitting on the floor, when I suddenly couldn't listen anymore.
25 years later.

Eventually I stopped going.  One semester I showed up to social studies 10 a handful of times because what was the point if I couldn't concentrate anyways?
But I thought it was my fault, personally.  I didn't even doubt it until a few months ago.

I didn't know how to explain that it wasn't that I didn't understand it - I almost literally couldn't hear something if it wasn't engaging.  It was like I'd just unintentionally end up in another universe mentally and FINALLY class would be done and I'd escape with 0 work done.

in his class.  He contacted all my teachers and asked for the bare minimum course work for me to complete with a month to go from graduation and made sure I finished it.
He is literally the only person that cared at all.
Everyone else just yelled and failed me and brushed me off.

No one bothered to ask why, instead it was a moral failing.
I only graduated because in grade 12 I hyper focused in my earth science class because my teacher was funny, kind, and interesting and one day he pulled me aside and asked me why I was failing everything but excelling

Since being diagnosed with ADHD a day after turning 32 I've been thinking.
Why, instead of putting me in "stupid" spelling/math, failing me multiple times for certain classes, calling home DAILY to get me in trouble.. did no one ask why.
Why did some kids get help and I didn't.
